    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1949-07-23T00:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1949-07-23T00:30:00-05:00" n="348"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d348">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">890.20/7–2349: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in India</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Henderson</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">New Delhi</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1949-07-23T11:00:00+05:30"
                            >July 23, 1949—11 a. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>833. Bajpai,<note n="1" xml:id="d348fn1">Sir Girja Shankar Bajpai,
                        Secretary-General of the Indian Ministry of External Affairs.</note>
                    External Affairs, tells me that: <list>
                        <label>1.</label>
                        <item>Several days ago Philippine Ambassador Elizalde approached Madame
                                Pandit<note n="2" xml:id="d348fn2">Mme. Vijaya Lakshmi Pandit,
                                Indian Ambassador in the United States.</note> telling her his
                            government instructed him inquire whether <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                                >GOI</gloss>
                            <note n="3" xml:id="d348fn3">Government of India.</note> would be
                            prepared enter discussions with Philippine Govt re recent
                            Philippine-Chinese anti-Commie pact and re possibility <gloss
                                target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> associating itself with other Asian
                            countries in coordinating endeavor halt march Communism in Asia.</item>
                        <label>2.</label>
                        <item>
                            <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss> instructed Madame Pandit inform
                            Elizalde to effect that although <gloss target="#t_GOI1">GOI</gloss>
                            usually ready discuss any international matters with Philippine Govt, it
                            believes would be unwise so soon after announcement Philippine-Chinese
                            pact to enter discussions which might create impression that Asian
                            powers were ganging up against Soviet Union.</item>
                        <label>3.</label>
                        <item>When Madame Pandit gave this message Elizalde, he said he had expected
                            reply this character, in fact he had been given to understand US Govt
                            had feelings similar to that of <gloss target="#t_GOI1"
                            >GOI</gloss>.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Henderson</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
